body:
When writing verilog, Yosys makes duplicate default clause. Some commercial tools consider this as an error.

```
    casez (in_a)
      2'b00:
        begin
          \$1\result[2:0]  = 3'b101;
        end
      2'b01:
        begin
          \$1\result[2:0]  = 3'b001;
        end
      default:
          \$1\result[2:0]  = 3'b000;
      default:
          \$1\result[2:0]  = 3'b000;
    endcase
```

This will make duplicate default.

```
module test (in_a, out_vt);

input [1:0] in_a;
output out_vt;
reg   [2:0] result;
assign out_vt = result;

always @(*)
  begin
     result    = 3'b000;  
     case (in_a)
       2'b00 : begin
          result = 3'b101;  
       end

       2'b01: begin
          result    = 3'b001;
       end

       default;

     endcase
  end
endmodule

```

This works.

```
module test (in_a, out_vt);
input [1:0] in_a;
output out_vt;
reg   [2:0] result;
assign out_vt = result;

always @(*)
  begin
     result    = 3'b000;  
     case (in_a)
       2'b00 : begin
          result = 3'b101;  
       end

       2'b01: begin
          result    = 3'b001;
       end

       default:
        begin
        end

     endcase
  end
endmodule
```

